column6: I feel like my first two weeks hypothesis is somewhat based correctly as I noticed I have a lot more reviews in text sentences than audio ones, IIRC, it was nearly double one day. I either tend to fail these ones more or unintentionally put sentences with words with too difficult to remember kanji in them. I've noticed that I've started putting easier sentences, but with kanji I interpret as more important to visually learn, in text sentences. Audio sentence reps go by significantly faster and I tend to remember them way easier though I'm worried I'm not actually learning the kanji I don't know in some words.
Recalling the kanji on Audio cards is mighty hard, but I feel it will help with reading later.

it's hard to find enough time to equal my raw immersion time with my subbed time; I usually find 2-3 good 1T sentences in a show. Sentence card words feel slightly more easy to recognize in immersion.
I think the order of the audio should be flipped so the sentence audio plays before the word audio.

One thing I noticed is that, even though I like audio sentences better, finding perfect ones is so much harder. I'm always a little relieved when I'm collecting text ones cause I can use audio that's a little fast or slurred without being worried that it'll end up being a super hard card.
Sometimes it can be easy to slip in to a repetition and lose some of the critical thinking aspect to reviews or learning cards. I don't think this is new, more that I've been reminded of it.
I really need to change my review schedule, 4 am review sessions are killing me...
